  <content>
    <title>Experimentation at Scale</title>

    <summary>Run 100+ experiments/year with statistical rigor. Pre-register hypotheses, behavioral predictions, guardrail metrics, and decision rules to prevent HiPPO override and build org learning.</summary>

    <why>
      <p>Ad-hoc A/B testing does not build organizational learning — results are siloed, hypotheses are solution-shaped, and decisions are overridden by opinion. A scaled experimentation platform converts every product bet into a falsifiable, time-bounded test with a pre-committed verdict rule. Microsoft runs ~100k experiments/year; the competitive gap between ad-hoc and scaled orgs compounds with each roadmap cycle.</p>
    </why>

    <when-to-use>
      <list>
        <item>A roadmap bet is reversible, has a clear behavioral prediction, and can be measured within 4 weeks at current traffic.</item>
        <item>Quarterly planning when roadmap candidates outnumber conviction — turn opinions into a ranked experiment slate.</item>
        <item>After discovery rounds where 2–4 candidate solutions exist for one opportunity — experiment to pick, not to launch.</item>
        <item>A guardrail-only "do-no-harm" rollout: PM wants to ship a refactor or migration and needs proof it didn't regress conversion/retention.</item>
        <item>A pricing or packaging change where finance wants quantified lift before commit (with legal sign-off on bait-pricing rules).</item>
        <item>Stakeholder disputes (design vs. eng vs. growth) where pre-registering a metric and accepting the verdict is faster than politics.</item>
        <item>Planning org experimentation infrastructure: choosing tooling (GrowthBook vs. Statsig vs. Eppo), governance, and statistical standards.</item>
        <item>Onboarding a new PM into an experiment-mature org — agentized hypothesis review tightens the loop fast.</item>
      </list>
    </when-to-use>

    <when-not-to-use>
      <list>
        <item>Strategic, irreversible bets (rebrand, repositioning, contract terms) — A/B will under-power on the metrics that matter and over-emphasize short-term proxies. Use evidence triangulation instead.</item>
        <item>Pre-PMF (less than 1k WAU): the PM should be doing problem interviews, not optimizing CTAs. A null result here means "no signal," not "no effect."</item>
        <item>Innovation-tier features where the audience needs greater than 30 days to learn the new behavior — novelty/primacy will dominate the readout.</item>
        <item>Internal tooling, B2B with fewer than 50 accounts, or one-off launches (regulatory, marketing event). Use cohort/case-study analysis.</item>
        <item>When the PM cannot articulate a falsifiable behavioral prediction with a numeric MDE — that is a discovery gap, not an experiment gap. Run a fake-door, prototype test, or interview round first.</item>
        <item>Surfaces under compliance review (HIPAA, PCI, KYC) where any variant requires legal sign-off — gating loop is slower than the agentic experiment author; default to risk-controlled rollout, not A/B.</item>
        <item>When success can only be measured greater than 1 quarter out (LTV, retention beyond available holdout) — switch to switchback or holdout-cohort analysis with explicit stakeholder agreement.</item>
      </list>
    </when-not-to-use>

    <section name="failure-modes-and-limitations">
      <antipattern>
        <description>HiPPO override: even with a clean readout, leadership ships the loser anyway. Without a written decision rule pre-committed by the exec sponsor, experimentation becomes theatre.</description>
        <reason>Pre-register the decision rule, not just the metric — written, signed by sponsor, archived in Notion. Without this, "we won" becomes negotiable.</reason>
      </antipattern>

      <antipattern>
        <description>"Experiment to launch, not to learn": PM ships the variant once it crosses 95% CI without checking guardrails — guardrails fail, ops gets paged, trust in the platform erodes.</description>
        <reason>Surface guardrail breaches BEFORE primary metric in the narrative. All readouts must enumerate stop-conditions and check SRM and power before reading lift.</reason>
      </antipattern>

      <antipattern>
        <description>Solution-shaped hypotheses: "we should add a banner" — the hypothesis carries the answer. PM agents must rewrite to behavioral if-then-because before any sample-size math runs.</description>
        <reason>Force a behavioral if-then-because hypothesis. "Try a banner" is rejected; "If we surface plan upgrades in-context, then trial-to-paid will move +3% because friction at the upgrade moment is the bottleneck" is accepted.</reason>
      </antipattern>

      <antipattern>
        <description>Metric tunnel-vision: PM optimizes the KPI in their OKR; the experiment moves the KPI but cannibalizes a sibling team's metric. Cross-team guardrails are the fix, not heroic monitoring.</description>
        <reason>Every experiment MUST enumerate guardrail metrics that represent adjacent team outcomes. Surface guardrail breaches before concluding the experiment won.</reason>
      </antipattern>

      <antipattern>
        <description>Local maxima: 18 months of CTA color tests yield 6% lift and zero strategic learning. Without an opportunity-tree-rooted slate, experimentation drifts to micro-optimizations.</description>
        <reason>Tie every experiment to one opportunity-tree node; if it doesn't link, it's a CTA test, not product work — schedule, but cap to ≤25% of slate.</reason>
      </antipattern>

      <antipattern>
        <description>Prioritization blind spot: agents will rank by ICE without checking dependency on long-running platform work, then surface a "ship-now" candidate that needs a 6-week migration first.</description>
        <reason>Feed the eng dep graph into the ranker prompt. ICE/RICE rankers will rank a 6-week dependency-locked experiment above a ready-to-go one because they ignore deps.</reason>
      </antipattern>

      <antipattern>
        <description>Reading outcomes wrong: "p=0.08, directionally positive" → ship. PM agents will defer to whichever framing matches the PM's prior unless forced to copy verbatim framework output.</description>
        <reason>Pin temperature ≤0.1 and force JSON output with explicit verdict enum. Readout-interpreter must check SRM and power before reading lift; reorder prompt to fail fast on invalid experiments.</reason>
      </antipattern>

      <antipattern>
        <description>Communication failure: a clean win in one segment, flat overall — PM ships globally citing "the win." Segmented readout is mandatory; segment cuts must be pre-registered to avoid p-hacking.</description>
        <reason>Pre-register segment cuts (max 5). Post-hoc segments are exploratory only and labelled as such — never drive ship decisions. Surface all segment cuts in the decision narrative.</reason>
      </antipattern>
    </section>

    <section name="agentic-workflow-pm-side">
      <p>PM-side agents focus on framing, prioritization, decision, and narrative. Statistics, flags, SRM, and metric registry are delegated to product-operations agents (see sibling doc). Human-in-the-loop checkpoints: hypothesis approval (PM + design), decision rule sign-off (PM + sponsor), ship/kill call (PM only).</p>

      <p>Weekly workflow:</p>

      <code lang="text"><![CDATA[
Backlog        → idea-triager (sonnet)         → testable? + feeds opportunity tree
Hypothesis     → hypothesis-author (sonnet)    → if-then-because, MDE, primary, segment cuts
Prioritize     → ice-rice-ranker (haiku)       → ranked slate, dep-aware
Pre-flight     → assumption-mapper (sonnet)    → list of stop-conditions + decision rule
Pre-flight     → ops-platform agents           → sample size, guardrails, flags (delegated)
Decision       → readout-interpreter (opus)    → ship / iterate / kill / extend
Comms          → stakeholder-narrator (sonnet) → exec memo, slack/loom blurb, OKR delta
Post-launch    → learning-curator (opus)       → links experiment → opportunity-tree node
]]></code>

      <rule testable="true">
        <statement>Idea-triager (sonnet): On idea intake. Input: Idea text, opportunity tree, traffic estimate. Output: Testability score + tier (A/B, prototype, qual, irreversible). Cheap models for collection and triage.</statement>
        <rationale>Sonnet for structured task decomposition. Triage gates ideas before PM invests in hypothesis authoring.</rationale>
      </rule>

      <rule testable="true">
        <statement>Hypothesis-author (sonnet): Per candidate idea. Input: Idea, opportunity tree node, prior experiments. Output: experiment-doc.md with if-then-because, primary metric, MDE. Reject if hypothesis names a feature instead of a behavior change. Reject if MDE is missing or > likely effect by 3x. Require prior_evidence: field with at least 2 sources.</statement>
        <rationale>Sonnet for structured authoring. Hypothesis-author must enforce behavioral framing and evidence requirements before any sample-size math runs.</rationale>
      </rule>

      <rule testable="true">
        <statement>Ice-rice-ranker (haiku): Weekly slate. Input: Hypothesis pool, eng dep graph, current OKRs. Output: Ranked slate with confidence, effort, reach, dep flags. Feed eng dep graph; ranker will otherwise ignore 6-week blockers.</statement>
        <rationale>Haiku for ranking math. Dep awareness prevents surface of ready-to-ship ideas that actually depend on long-running work.</rationale>
      </rule>

      <rule testable="true">
        <statement>Assumption-mapper (sonnet): Pre-launch. Input: Hypothesis, surface. Output: Falsifiable assumptions + stop conditions + decision rule. Pair every experiment with a kill criterion before launch.</statement>
        <rationale>Sonnet for structured writing. Stop-conditions make the kill threshold explicit and prevent PM bias toward shipping.</rationale>
      </rule>

      <rule testable="true">
        <statement>Readout-interpreter (opus): At decision point. Input: Ops readout JSON, hypothesis doc, segment cuts. Output: Verdict (ship/iterate/kill/extend) + caveats. Check SRM and power before reading lift. Fail fast on invalid experiments. Surface guardrail breaches BEFORE primary metric. Surface novelty risk if runtime less than 14 days OR engagement metric.</statement>
        <rationale>Opus for verdict synthesis where misreading is expensive. Fail-fast on validity checks prevents nicely worded ship memos on broken assignments.</rationale>
      </rule>

      <rule testable="true">
        <statement>Stakeholder-narrator (sonnet): At decision point. Input: Verdict, OKR map, audience. Output: Exec memo, slack blurb, ticket update. Force verbatim copy of CI low/high; never paraphrase. Never round confidence intervals ("4% lift, 95% confidence") into clean numbers.</statement>
        <rationale>Sonnet for narrative writing. Verbatim numbers prevent stakeholders from misinterpreting precision.</rationale>
      </rule>

      <rule testable="true">
        <statement>Learning-curator (opus): Monthly. Input: All closed experiments. Output: Opportunity-tree edits, "patterns we found", "patterns we killed". Require N>=5 with shared opportunity-tree branch before emitting a "pattern" claim. Do not hallucinate patterns from N=2 experiments.</statement>
        <rationale>Opus for synthesis. Monthly curation links experiments back to the discovery tree, building org memory and preventing local-maxima drifts.</rationale>
      </rule>

      <rule testable="true">
        <statement>Roadmap-impact-modeler (sonnet): Quarterly. Input: Closed experiments, OKR tree. Output: Adjusted forecast for next quarter's roadmap. Emit ranges and label assumptions; never single-number forecasts. Do not compound point estimates into 4-quarter forecasts and report as fact.</statement>
        <rationale>Sonnet for structured writing. Range forecasts prevent the illusion of precision and flag assumptions explicitly.</rationale>
      </rule>
    </section>

    <section name="hypothesis-and-readout-schemas">
      <p>Hypothesis intake schema (hypothesis-doc.yaml). The central artifact for pre-registration:</p>

      <code lang="yaml"><![CDATA[
id: exp_2026-04-onboarding-checklist
opportunity_tree_node: opp.activation.first-value
hypothesis: |
  If we replace the static onboarding video with a 3-step interactive checklist,
  then day-7 activation rate will increase by >= 4% (relative)
  because users self-direct to first-value tasks faster (evidence: 12 interviews, 3 prototype tests).
primary_metric: d7_activation_rate
guardrail_metrics:
  - signup_to_login_latency_p95
  - support_tickets_per_signup
mde_relative: 0.04
power: 0.8
alpha: 0.05
runtime_min_days: 14
segment_cuts: [device, plan, signup_source]
decision_rule: |
  SHIP if primary_lift >= 4% AND ci_low > 0 AND no guardrail breach AND no SRM.
  ITERATE if 0 < primary_lift < 4% AND no guardrail breach.
  KILL if primary_lift <= 0 OR guardrail breach.
  EXTEND if power_achieved < 0.7 AND no guardrail breach.
stop_conditions:
  - support_tickets_per_signup spike > 25% week-over-week
  - p95 signup latency > 1.5x baseline for >24h
sponsor: vp-product@team
prior_evidence:
  - dovetail/study-2026-03-onboarding-pain
  - maze/proto-2026-04-checklist-v3
  - exp_2025-Q4-onboarding-video (null result)
]]></code>

      <p>Readout interpretation rules (embedded in readout-interpreter prompt):</p>

      <code lang="text"><![CDATA[
<role>You are readout-interpreter. You copy framework numbers verbatim. You never paraphrase confidence.</role>

<inputs>
  ops_readout: { lift, ci_low, ci_high, p_value, srm_pass, power_achieved, segment_breakdown }
  hypothesis_doc: <pre-registered>
</inputs>

<rules>
- If srm_pass=false: VERDICT=invalid, recommend rerun, do not interpret lift.
- If power_achieved < 0.7: VERDICT=inconclusive, recommend extend or kill, never ship.
- Apply pre-registered decision rule; if rule silent, VERDICT=defer to PM.
- Surface guardrail breaches BEFORE primary metric in the narrative.
- Surface novelty risk if runtime < 14 days OR engagement metric.
- Output: { verdict: ship|iterate|kill|extend|invalid, primary_evidence, caveats[], next_step }
]]></code>
    </section>

    <section name="idea-triage-script">
      <p>Idea-triage helper (scripts/triage_idea.py, ~30 lines). Scores idea testability and routes to tier:</p>

      <code lang="python"><![CDATA[
import json, sys
SCORES = {"reversible": 1, "irreversible": 0, "behavior_change": 1, "feature_only": 0}
TIER = {3: "A/B", 2: "prototype-or-A/B", 1: "qual-first", 0: "irreversible-strategic"}

def triage(idea: dict) -> dict:
    score = 0
    score += SCORES["reversible" if idea.get("reversible") else "irreversible"]
    score += 1 if idea.get("min_traffic_ok") else 0
    score += SCORES["behavior_change" if idea.get("behavioral_prediction") else "feature_only"]
    return {"score": score, "tier": TIER[score], "rationale": idea.get("notes", "")}

if __name__ == "__main__":
    idea = json.load(sys.stdin)
    json.dump(triage(idea), sys.stdout)
]]></code>
    </section>

    <section name="best-practices">
      <p>Operational discipline for experiment governance:</p>

      <rule testable="true">
        <statement>Pre-register the decision rule, not just the metric — written, signed by sponsor, archived in Notion. Without this, "we won" becomes negotiable.</statement>
        <rationale>Decision rules encode what "victory" means before the data arrives. Otherwise, post-hoc interpretation drifts based on leadership politics.</rationale>
      </rule>

      <rule testable="true">
        <statement>Tie every experiment to one opportunity-tree node; if it doesn't link, it's a CTA test, not product work — schedule, but cap to ≤25% of slate.</statement>
        <rationale>Opportunity-linked experiments build strategic learning. Capping CTA tests prevents drift into micro-optimizations that look productive but don't inform roadmap.</rationale>
      </rule>

      <rule testable="true">
        <statement>Keep one primary metric per experiment. PM agents will be tempted to add "secondary primary"; reject in review.</statement>
        <rationale>Multiple primary metrics introduce p-hacking risk and bury the main hypothesis in noise.</rationale>
      </rule>

      <rule testable="true">
        <statement>Pre-register segment cuts (max 5). Post-hoc segments are exploratory only and labelled as such — never drive ship decisions.</statement>
        <rationale>Pre-registration prevents p-hacking. Exploratory segments are valid for hypothesis generation but not for decisions.</rationale>
      </rule>

      <rule testable="true">
        <statement>Treat null results as findings, not failures. Add to learning-curator inputs; over time, a pattern of nulls in a region of the opportunity tree means rethink the opportunity.</statement>
        <rationale>Null results rule out hypotheses and redirect discovery effort. Patterns of nulls in one branch signal the team is chasing a mirage.</rationale>
      </rule>

      <rule testable="true">
        <statement>Run a quarterly "decisions we got wrong" memo with sponsor — single highest-leverage org-learning loop.</statement>
        <rationale>Quarterly calibration prevents the team from repeating mistakes and surfaces systemic issues (e.g., "we keep over-weighting novelty effects").</rationale>
      </rule>

      <rule testable="true">
        <statement>Cap PM time on experiment ops to less than 20%. If it's higher, the platform isn't mature enough; push work back to product-ops or invest in tooling.</statement>
        <rationale>Experiment ops is overhead; it should not dominate PM cycles. If it does, it signals weak tooling or governance.</rationale>
      </rule>

      <rule testable="true">
        <statement>Always pair an experiment with a kill criterion before launch. PMs are biased to ship; the kill rule is the only thing that keeps the slate honest.</statement>
        <rationale>Kill criteria make the downside explicit and prevent sunk-cost fallacy from extending dead-end experiments.</rationale>
      </rule>

      <rule testable="true">
        <statement>Maintain a living opportunity-tree map; learning-curator edits it after every closed experiment so future PMs see why a path was abandoned.</statement>
        <rationale>Org memory prevents the same hypothesis from being re-tested in 18 months. Documented abandonment is as valuable as documented wins.</rationale>
      </rule>
    </section>

    <section name="ai-agent-gotchas">
      <p>Common failure modes when automating experiment workflows:</p>

      <antipattern>
        <description>Agents will turn ambiguous PM intent ("can we improve activation?") into a hypothesis without flagging missing evidence.</description>
        <reason>Require a prior_evidence: field with at least 2 sources; hypothesis-author refuses to output if missing.</reason>
      </antipattern>

      <antipattern>
        <description>Readout-interpreter under temperature > 0.2 will narrate "directionally positive" on null results.</description>
        <reason>Pin temperature ≤0.1 and force JSON output with explicit verdict enum.</reason>
      </antipattern>

      <antipattern>
        <description>Decision rules drift between hypothesis-doc and readout — narrator agent should compute a hash of the hypothesis-doc at launch and refuse to render a ship memo if the hash changed.</description>
        <reason>Hypothesis immutability is critical. If PM rewrites the decision rule after seeing the readout, the experiment is invalid.</reason>
      </antipattern>

      <antipattern>
        <description>ICE/RICE rankers will rank a 6-week dependency-locked experiment above a ready-to-go one because they ignore deps.</description>
        <reason>Feed the eng dep graph into the ranker prompt.</reason>
      </antipattern>

      <antipattern>
        <description>Stakeholder-narrator will round confidence intervals into clean numbers ("4% lift, 95% confidence").</description>
        <reason>Force verbatim copy of CI low/high; never paraphrase.</reason>
      </antipattern>

      <antipattern>
        <description>Learning-curator will hallucinate a pattern from N=2 closed experiments.</description>
        <reason>Require N>=5 with shared opportunity-tree branch before emitting a "pattern" claim.</reason>
      </antipattern>

      <antipattern>
        <description>HiPPO leak: if the agent has access to leadership chat, it will weight comments as "evidence".</description>
        <reason>Keep prior_evidence sources to artifact links only (Dovetail study IDs, prior experiments, prototype tests). No Slack or email.</reason>
      </antipattern>

      <antipattern>
        <description>Readout-interpreter must check SRM and power before reading lift; reorder prompt to fail fast on invalid experiments.</description>
        <reason>Otherwise opus will write a nicely worded ship memo on a broken assignment.</reason>
      </antipattern>

      <antipattern>
        <description>Roadmap-impact-modeler will compound point estimates into 4-quarter forecasts and report them as fact.</description>
        <reason>Require it to emit ranges and to label assumptions, never single-number forecasts.</reason>
      </antipattern>

      <antipattern>
        <description>PM-only ship/kill: agents must not auto-execute the ship action; gate at the flag-deployer step.</description>
        <reason>If autonomy is dialed up, require dual-key approval from PM and sponsor.</reason>
      </antipattern>

      <antipattern>
        <description>Translation drift (Ukrainian PM input ↔ English experiment doc): hypothesis-author should round-trip-translate the if-then-because and surface differences before approval.</description>
        <reason>Otherwise nuance about "first-value" or "activation" gets lost.</reason>
      </antipattern>

      <antipattern>
        <description>Token cost: readout-interpreter on a 12-segment readout balloons.</description>
        <reason>Cap at 50k tokens; otherwise summarize segments first, then interpret.</reason>
      </antipattern>
    </section>

    <section name="hypothesis-authoring-prompt">
      <p>Example prompt pattern for hypothesis-author agent:</p>

      <prompt purpose="hypothesis-authoring"><![CDATA[
<role>You are hypothesis-author for a senior PM. You refuse solution-shaped hypotheses.</role>

<schema>
  hypothesis: "If <behavior change>, then <metric M> will <move> by <Δ>, because <mechanism>."
  primary_metric: <one metric, from registry>
  mde_relative: <0.005..0.20>
  segment_cuts: <pre-registered, max 5>
  stop_conditions: <guardrail breaches that must trigger kill>
  decision_rule: <"ship if primary +X% with no guardrail breach and..">
</schema>

<rules>
- Reject if hypothesis names a feature instead of a behavior change.
- Reject if MDE is missing or > likely effect by 3x (overpowered, waste).
- Reject if primary metric is not in `metric-catalog.yaml`.
- Reject if decision rule allows ad-hoc judgment ("we'll see").
- Output JSON to schema; markdown digest <= 60 lines.
</rules>
]]></prompt>
    </section>

